### Musical settings

*   Emerson's "[Concord Hymn](/Concord_Hymn)," penned for Concord's [Independence Day](/Independence_Day_(United_States)) celebration on July 4, 1837, was both read and sung as a hymn on that occasion, utilizing the then-popular tune "[Old Hundredth](/Old_100th)".
*   [Charles Ives](/Charles_Ives) set a fragment from Emerson's poem "Voluntaries" (a tribute to soldiers fighting for the [Union](/Union_(American_Civil_War))) as a song titled "Duty," included in his collection *114 Songs* (1919–24).
*   [Ernst Toch](/Ernst_Toch) set Emerson's poem "Good-Bye" as the sixth and final movement of his composition *The Inner Circle*, for [mixed chorus](/Mixed_chorus) a cappella (composed 1945, revised 1953).
*   Three fragments from Emerson's essay "Spiritual Laws" (from [Essays: First Series](/Essays:_First_Series), 1841) form the structural basis of [Kaija Saariaho](/Kaija_Saariaho)'s *True Fire* for baritone and orchestra (2014), a work that incorporates texts from various sources. The title of the work is derived from the essay's concluding sentence, which also ends the musical setting: "We know the authentic effects of the true fire through every one of its million disguises."

